static Optional<PageFilter> allOf(List<PageFilter> filters)
{
    if (filters.isEmpty()) {
        return Optional.empty();
    }
    if (filters.size() == 1) {
        return Optional.of(filters.get(0));
    }
    PageFilter[] filterArray = filters.toArray(new PageFilter[0]);
    return Optional.of((page, positions) -> {
        Positions retained = positions;
        for (PageFilter filter : filterArray) {
            retained = filter.filterPositions(page, retained);
            if (retained.isEmpty()) {
                break;
            }
        }
        return retained;
    });
}
```

The critical difference is that PageFilter.allOf chains filterPositions calls together without calling selectPositions between them. It accumulates retained positions through each filter, then calls selectPositions once at the end via applyFilter. This contrasts with the old RowPredicate approach where each predicate would independently call selectPositions on the page, potentially causing issues with dictionary-backed blocks when multiple filters were applied sequentially.
